const e=["Ovulated cell is a secondary oocyte arrested in metaphase II","Fertilization occurs in the ampulla of the uterine tube","Capacitation occurs in the female reproductive tract","Gastrulation (Week 3) forms three germ layers: ectoderm, mesoderm, endoderm","Neural crest cells (from ectoderm) give rise to dentin, pulp, cementum","Enamel is derived from oral ectoderm (NOT neural crest)","Tongue muscles derive from occipital somites (NOT pharyngeal arches)","Anterior neuropore failure causes anencephaly; posterior causes spina bifida","Placenta = chorion frondosum (fetal) + decidua basalis (maternal)","IgG crosses placenta; IgM does not (used to detect fetal infection)"],n='\n# EMBRYOGENESIS ‚Äî SUMMARY\n\nI\'ve put together a summary with some clinical points relevant to pregnancy.\n\n**Quick overview video:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4n2H2eQOmc8\n\n**Deeper study:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H5hqwZRnBBw&list=PLTF9h-T1TcJjUxgs0dqyDCaS-glauXcsL (Videos 1‚Äì8, skip 7, and video 19). Focus especially on ectoderm, mesoderm, pharyngeal arches, and neural crest cells.\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">**Heads up** ‚Äî I would not spend too much time on embryology honestly. In my exam there wasn\'t a single question on it, except for the arches. But just to be safe, I made a summary anyway.</span>\n\nArches are a separate topic in oral histology as it was in paper 2 mostly. Therefore I have not added much MCQ as well.\n\n---\n\n## EVENTS BEFORE FERTILIZATION\n\n### 1Ô∏è‚É£ Oogenesis (starts before birth)\n\n- Primordial germ cells ‚Üí oogonia\n- Oogonia undergo mitosis ‚Üí primary oocytes\n- Primary oocytes:\n  - Enter meiosis I\n  - Arrest in **prophase I (diplotene phase)**\n- Before birth the primary oocytes are formed and are arrested in prophase (diplotene phase)\n- Present at birth inside primordial follicles\n\n| Stage | Oocyte Type | Key Histological Features |\n|-------|-------------|---------------------------|\n| Primordial Follicle | Primary Oocyte | Single layer of flat (squamous) follicular cells; dormant in the outer cortex |\n| Primary Follicle | Primary Oocyte | Follicular cells become cuboidal (now called granulosa cells). Zona pellucida begins to form |\n| Secondary Follicle | Primary Oocyte | Multiple layers of granulosa cells; development of theca interna and externa layers |\n| Antral (Tertiary) | Primary Oocyte | Appearance of a fluid-filled cavity called the antrum |\n| Graafian (Mature) | Secondary Oocyte | Large, dominant follicle; antrum is huge. Oocyte is pushed to the side on a mound of cells (cumulus oophorus) |\n\n### 3Ô∏è‚É£ Graafian follicle ‚Äî IMPORTANT DETAILS\n\nContains:\n- Secondary oocyte\n- Zona pellucida\n- Corona radiata\n- Large antrum\n- Large antrum\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image11.png" alt="Graafian Follicle" width="500" />\n</div>\n\n\nJust before ovulation:\n- Primary oocyte completes meiosis I\n- Forms:\n  - Secondary oocyte\n  - First polar body\n\nSecondary oocyte:\n- Arrests in **metaphase II**\n- This is the cell that is ovulated\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">üìå **Ovulated cell = secondary oocyte (NOT ovum)**</span>\n\n### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Ovulation\n\n- Triggered by **LH surge**\n- Rupture of the Graafian follicle leads to formation of the corpus hemorrhagicum, which later becomes the corpus luteum\n- Immediately after ovulation ‚Üí corpus hemorrhagicum\n- Hormone-secreting structure ‚Üí corpus luteum\n- White scar ‚Üí corpus albicans (if no fertilization occurs)\n\nSecondary oocyte released into:\n- Peritoneal cavity\n- Captured by fimbriae of uterine tube\n\n<span style="color: #ff9900">**Membrane ‚Üí Zona ‚Üí Space ‚Üí Corona**</span> (layers of 2ndry oocyte - important to remember because sperm passes through these)\n\nOocyte enters **ampulla** of tube\n\n---\n\n## üîµ B. MALE SIDE ‚Äî SPERMATOGENESIS & SPERM MATURATION\n\n### 5Ô∏è‚É£ Spermatogenesis (in seminiferous tubules)\n\nSpermatogonia ‚Üí mitosis ‚Üí primary spermatocytes\nMeiosis I ‚Üí secondary spermatocytes\nMeiosis II ‚Üí spermatids\nSpermatids mature into spermatozoa\n\n| Stage | Chromosome status | Ploidy |\n|-------|-------------------|--------|\n| Spermatogonia | 46 chromosomes (2n) | Diploid |\n| Primary spermatocyte | 46 chromosomes (DNA replicated ‚Üí 4C) | Diploid |\n| Secondary spermatocyte | 23 chromosomes (2C) | Haploid |\n| Spermatid | 23 chromosomes (1C) | Haploid |\n| Spermatozoa | 23 chromosomes | Haploid |\n\n### 6Ô∏è‚É£ Structure of sperm\n\n- **Head:** Nucleus + Acrosome (enzymes: hyaluronidase, acrosin)\n- **Neck**\n- **Middle piece:** Mitochondria (energy)\n- **Tail:** Motility - the sperm flagellum is composed of an axoneme with a **9+2 microtubule arrangement**\n\n| Structure | Arrangement |\n|-----------|-------------|\n| Centriole / Basal body | 9 √ó 3 (9+0) |\n| Cilia / Flagella (axoneme) | 9 + 2 |\n\n### Capacitation (CRUCIAL STEP BEFORE FERTILIZATION)\n\n**Occurs in:** Female reproductive tract (uterus & tube)\n\n**What happens:**\n- Removal of glycoprotein coat from sperm head\n- Increased membrane permeability\n- Sperm becomes:\n  - Hyperactive\n  - Capable of acrosome reaction\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">üìå **Only capacitated sperm can fertilize**</span>\n\n---\n\n## üß† ONE-LINE EXAM ANSWERS\n\n- Ovulated cell ‚Üí **secondary oocyte**\n- Oocyte arrested in **metaphase II**\n- Capacitation occurs in **female tract**\n- Site of fertilization ‚Üí **ampulla of uterine tube**\n\n---\n\n## 1Ô∏è‚É£ Fertilization\n\nOccurs in the **ampulla of the uterine tube**.\n\nSperm move into the egg in this order: <span style="color: #ff9900">**Corona ‚Üí Zona ‚Üí Space ‚Üí Membrane**</span>\n\nFusion of sperm and ovum forms the **zygote**.\n\nSecondary oocyte was arrested in metaphase II. Fertilization triggers:\n- Completion of meiosis II\n- Formation of:\n  - Mature ovum\n  - Second polar body\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">üìå First polar body ‚Üí from meiosis I</span>\n<span style="color: #ff0000">üìå Second polar body ‚Üí after fertilization</span>\n\nRestores the diploid number (46 chromosomes). Formation of **zygote** occurs.\n\n### 2Ô∏è‚É£ Cleavage\n\n- Rapid mitotic divisions of the zygote\n- No increase in overall size\n- Forms: **Morula** (16‚Äì32 cells)\n\n### 3Ô∏è‚É£ Blastocyst Formation\n\nThe Morula enters the uterus and becomes the **blastocyst**.\n\nCells in the morula decide to either clump together on one side (inner cell mass) or go to the wall side forming the wall.\n\nThe Blastocyst consists of:\n- **Trophoblast** ‚Üí Placenta\n- **Inner cell mass (embryoblast)** ‚Üí Embryo\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image3.png" alt="Blastocyst Structure" width="500" />\n</div>\n\n\n### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Implantation\n\n- Occurs around **day 6‚Äì7**\n- The blastocyst embeds in the endometrium\n- The Trophoblast differentiates into:\n  - Cytotrophoblast\n  - Syncytiotrophoblast\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image2.png" alt="Implantation Timeline" width="600" />\n</div>\n\n\n### 5Ô∏è‚É£ Bilaminar Germ Disc (Week 2)\n\nThe Embryoblast differentiates into:\n- **Epiblast**\n- **Hypoblast**\n\nThe Amniotic cavity and yolk sac form during this week.\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image5.png" alt="Bilaminar Germ Disc" width="500" />\n</div>\n\n\n### 6Ô∏è‚É£ Gastrulation (Week 3) ‚Äî <span style="color: #ff0000">MOST IMPORTANT</span>\n\nFormation of three primary germ layers via the **primitive streak**.\n\nThe layers are:\n- Ectoderm\n- Mesoderm\n- Endoderm\n\nEstablishes the body axes.\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image6.png" alt="Gastrulation" width="600" />\n</div>\n\n\n---\n\n## 7Ô∏è‚É£ Germ Layer Derivatives (High-Yield)\n\n| Germ Layer | Derivatives (Examples) |\n|------------|------------------------|\n| **Ectoderm** | Epidermis, CNS & PNS, Oral epithelium, <span style="color: #ff0000">**Enamel**</span>, Neural crest cells, Pharyngeal cleft |\n| **Mesoderm** | Muscle, Bone, Cartilage, Blood vessels, Heart. In the head and neck region mesoderm and NCC (formed from ectoderm) both contribute ‚Äî called **ectomesenchymal tissue**. Pharyngeal arch |\n| **Endoderm** | Gut tube lining, Pharyngeal pouches, Respiratory epithelium |\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">‚ö†Ô∏è **IMPORTANT POINT** ‚Äî TONGUE MUSCLES ARE NOT FORMED BY THE PHARYNGEAL ARCH. THEY ARE DERIVED FROM THE **OCCIPITAL SOMITES**</span>\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">üìå **Exception: Palatoglossus**</span>\n- Derived from 4th pharyngeal arch\n- Supplied by vagus nerve (CN X)\n- The eye muscles are pre-optic somites\n\n### üß† ONE-GLANCE EXAM TABLE\n\n| Gland | Germ layer | Key point |\n|-------|------------|-----------|\n| Parotid | Ectoderm | Only major gland of ectodermal origin (serous) |\n| Submandibular | Endoderm | Mixed gland |\n| Sublingual | Endoderm | Mainly mucous |\n\n---\n\n## 8Ô∏è‚É£ Neurulation (Week 3‚Äì4)\n\n- Ectoderm forms the **neural plate**\n- The Neural plate rolls up to form the **neural tube**\n- The Neural tube develops into the brain and spinal cord\n- **Neural crest cells** migrate (crucial for craniofacial development)\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image13.png" alt="Neural Tube Formation" width="600" />\n</div>\n\n\n### üîë ONE-LINE EXAM ANSWERS\n\n| Defect | Cause | Time |\n|--------|-------|------|\n| <span style="color: #ff0000">Anterior neuropore failure</span> | ‚Üí Anencephaly | üìå Closure time: ~Day 25 |\n| <span style="color: #ff0000">Posterior neuropore failure</span> | ‚Üí Spina bifida | Closure time: ~Day 27 (only a hole in spine) |\n\n**Most severe spina bifida** ‚Üí Myelomeningocele (hole with spinal tissue)\n\n**Prevention** ‚Üí <span style="color: #ff0000">**Folic acid supplementation**</span>\n\nThe **notochord** is responsible for the initiation of neurulation. Later degenerates ‚Üí nucleus pulposus of intervertebral disc.\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image10.png" alt="Notochord and Vertebral Development" width="600" />\n</div>\n\n\n### Spina Bifida Types\n\n| Type | Key feature |\n|------|-------------|\n| Spina bifida occulta | Bony defect only, skin intact |\n| Meningocele | Meninges herniate |\n| Myelomeningocele | Meninges + spinal cord herniate (most severe) |\n| Rachischisis | Entire spinal cord exposed (rare, fatal) |\n\n---\n\n## 9Ô∏è‚É£ Body Folding (Week 4)\n\n- Converts the flat embryo into a cylindrical shape (cephalocaudal and lateral folding)\n- Forms the:\n  - Foregut (forms all organs of the abdomen related to GIT)\n  - Midgut\n  - Hindgut\n- Creates the **stomodeum** (primitive mouth)\n- **Oropharyngeal / buccopharyngeal membrane** separates the mouth from the gut\n\n---\n\n## üîü Pharyngeal Apparatus (Week 4) ‚Äî <span style="color: #ff0000">MOST IMPORTANT</span>\n\nPharyngeal arches, pouches, and clefts form.\n\nGive rise to structures of the:\n- Face\n- Neck\n- Oral cavity structures\n\n---\n\n## 1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Face & Palate Development (Weeks 4‚Äì10)\n\nFacial prominences form:\n- Frontonasal\n- Maxillary\n- Mandibular\n\n**Primary palate** develops from the intermaxillary segment.\n**Secondary palate** develops from the palatal shelves.\nFusion defects lead to **cleft lip/palate**.\n\n---\n\n## 1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ Tooth Development (Weeks 6‚Äì12)\n\n- **Oral ectoderm** ‚Üí Enamel\n- **Neural crest ectomesenchyme** ‚Üí Dentin, Pulp, Cementum\n\n### ü¶∑ TOOTH DEVELOPMENT ‚Äî KEY STAGES\n\n#### 1Ô∏è‚É£ Bud stage\n- Proliferation of dental lamina epithelium\n- Epithelial bud grows into underlying ectomesenchyme\n- ‚ùå Condensation is minimal here\n- **Bud stage ‚Üí epithelial proliferation**\n\n#### ‚úÖ 2Ô∏è‚É£ Cap stage\n- Enamel organ forms\n- Condensation of ectomesenchyme occurs, giving rise to:\n  - Dental papilla\n  - Dental follicle (dental sac)\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">üìå **Key point:** Cap stage = formation of enamel organ, dental papilla, and dental follicle</span>\n\n#### ‚úÖ 3Ô∏è‚É£ Bell stage\n- Tooth germ becomes bell-shaped\n- Cell differentiation occurs:\n  - Inner enamel epithelium ‚Üí ameloblasts\n  - Dental papilla cells ‚Üí odontoblasts\n- Histodifferentiation & morphodifferentiation occur\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">üìå **Key point:** Bell stage = shape determination + cell differentiation</span>\n\n### üîë FINAL EXAM\n\n- **Bud stage** ‚Äì epithelial proliferation\n- **Cap stage** ‚Äì formation of enamel organ, dental papilla, and dental follicle with mesenchymal condensation\n- **Bell stage** ‚Äì bell shape with cellular differentiation\n\n---\n\n## üß† PLACENTA ‚Äî SUMMARY\n\n### 1Ô∏è‚É£ Definition\n\nPlacenta is a temporary fetomaternal organ that allows exchange of gases, nutrients, wastes, and hormones between mother and fetus **without direct blood mixing**.\n\n### 2Ô∏è‚É£ Origin\n\n**Fetal part:**\n- Chorion frondosum\n- Derived from: Trophoblast + Extraembryonic mesoderm\n\n**Maternal part:**\n- Decidua basalis\n- Modified endometrium\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">üìå **Placenta = chorion frondosum (fetal) + decidua basalis (maternal)**</span>\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image7.png" alt="Fetal Development" width="500" />\n</div>\n\n\n### 3Ô∏è‚É£ Trophoblast differentiation\n\n- **Cytotrophoblast:** Inner, mitotically active layer\n- **Syncytiotrophoblast:** Outer multinucleated layer, invades endometrium, forms placental hormones\n\n### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Placental circulation\n\n- Maternal blood enters intervillous spaces\n- Fetal blood flows through chorionic villi\n- Exchange occurs across placental membrane\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">üìå **Maternal and fetal blood do NOT mix**</span>\n\n---\n\n## üß† CHORIONIC VILLI ‚Äî PRIMARY, SECONDARY & TERTIARY\n\n### üîë Core idea (memorize this first)\n\nVilli mature by adding layers:\n- Primary = cells only\n- Secondary = cells + mesoderm\n- Tertiary = cells + mesoderm + blood vessels\n\n| Feature | Primary villi | Secondary villi | Tertiary villi |\n|---------|--------------|-----------------|----------------|\n| Syncytiotrophoblast | ‚úî | ‚úî | ‚úî |\n| Cytotrophoblast | ‚úî | ‚úî | ‚úî |\n| Mesoderm | ‚úñ | ‚úî | ‚úî |\n| Blood vessels | ‚úñ | ‚úñ | ‚úî |\n| Function | Attachment | Structural support | Exchange |\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image1.png" alt="Chorionic Villi" width="600" />\n</div>\n\n\n### üîë ONE-LINE EXAM ANSWERS\n\n- Primary villi: trophoblast only\n- Secondary villi: mesoderm added\n- Tertiary villi: fetal blood vessels present\n- Gas & nutrient exchange begins at: **tertiary villus stage**\n\n### Umbilical Cord\n\nThe umbilical cord contains **2 arteries and 1 vein**.\n\n**2 Umbilical arteries:**\n- Carry deoxygenated blood and waste products\n- From fetus ‚Üí placenta\n\n**1 Umbilical vein:**\n- Carries oxygenated, nutrient-rich blood\n- From placenta ‚Üí fetus\n\n<span style="color: #ff9900">üìå **Mnemonic:** "Vein brings life, arteries take waste"</span>\n\n**One-line exam answer:** The umbilical cord normally has two arteries and one left vein.\n\n### 5Ô∏è‚É£ Placental membrane (barrier)\n\nInitially thick, later thins.\n\nComponents:\n- Syncytiotrophoblast\n- Cytotrophoblast (later disappears)\n- Basement membrane\n- Fetal capillary endothelium\n\n### 6Ô∏è‚É£ Placental Hormones\n\n- **hCG** ‚Üí maintains the corpus luteum (secreted by fetus), which secretes progesterone and estrogen\n- **Progesterone** ‚Üí maintains pregnancy\n- **Estrogen** ‚Üí uterine growth\n\n### 7Ô∏è‚É£ Immunological function\n\nActs as a selective barrier:\n- <span style="color: #ff0000">**IgG antibodies cross ‚Üí passive immunity to fetus**</span>\n- <span style="color: #ff0000">**IgM does NOT cross the placental barrier** ‚Äî therefore it is used to assess infection of the fetus</span>\n\n### ü©∫ Clinical application (VERY HIGH YIELD)\n\nUsed in diagnosis of **TORCH infections:**\n- **T**oxoplasmosis\n- **R**ubella\n- **C**MV\n- **H**SV\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">**Raised fetal/neonatal IgM = congenital infection**</span>\n\n- Most common congenital viral infection ‚Üí **CMV**\n- Rubella ‚Üí cataracts + deafness + heart disease\n- Syphilis ‚Üí **Hutchinson teeth**\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image12.png" alt="Hutchinson\'s Incisors" width="500" />\n</div>\n\n\n**Hutchinson incisors:** Permanent maxillary central incisors affected ‚Äî Screwdriver-shaped (narrow cervically, broad incisally)\n\n**Mulberry molars:** Occlusal surface shows multiple rounded enamel nodules, poorly developed cusps\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image4.png" alt="Mulberry Molars" width="500" />\n</div>\n\n\n### üß† ONE-LINE EXAM ANSWER\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">**IgM does not cross the placenta; therefore, its presence in the fetus indicates an intrauterine infection.**</span>\n\n### 8Ô∏è‚É£ Substances that CAN cross placenta\n\n- Alcohol\n- Nicotine\n- Drugs (e.g., phenytoin)\n- Viruses (TORCH infections)\n- Carbon monoxide\n- Glucose by facilitated diffusion\n- Local anesthetic by facilitated diffusion\n\n---\n\n## üìã SUMMARY POINTS\n\n- Placenta is formed by (fetal) chorion frondosum and (maternal) decidua basalis\n- hCG is secreted by syncytiotrophoblast\n- IgG crosses placenta\n- Maternal and fetal blood do not mix\n\n---\n\n## üî¨ Clinical relevance (dentistry & medicine)\n\n- Drugs given to pregnant patients may affect fetus\n- Infections during pregnancy can cause congenital anomalies\n- Hypoxia affects craniofacial development\n\n### Analgesics in Pregnancy\n\n| Drug | Pregnancy Safety |\n|------|-----------------|\n| Paracetamol | ‚úÖ Safe (DOC) |\n| Ibuprofen | ‚ö†Ô∏è 1st‚Äì2nd trimester only |\n| Aspirin | ‚ùå Harmful |\n| Codeine | ‚ùå Harmful |\n| Tramadol | ‚ùå Harmful |\n| Diclofenac | ‚ùå Harmful (esp. 3rd trimester) |\n\n- <span style="color: #ff0000">**Analgesic of choice in pregnancy ‚Üí Paracetamol**</span>\n- NSAIDs contraindicated in 3rd trimester\n- Aspirin avoided due to bleeding & ductus arteriosus closure\n\n---\n\n## üö´ Antibiotics CONTRAINDICATED in Lactation\n\n### ‚ùå ABSOLUTELY / GENERALLY CONTRAINDICATED\n\n**1. Tetracyclines (Doxycycline, Tetracycline)**\n- Excreted in breast milk\n- Causes: Tooth discoloration, Inhibition of bone growth\n- ‚ùå Avoid in lactation\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image8.png" alt="Tetracycline Staining" width="500" />\n</div>\n\n\n**2. Chloramphenicol**\n- Risk of **gray baby syndrome**\n- Bone marrow suppression\n- ‚ùå Strictly contraindicated\n\n**3. Fluoroquinolones (Ciprofloxacin, Ofloxacin, Levofloxacin)**\n- Risk of: Cartilage damage, Arthropathy\n- ‚ùå Avoid (especially long-term use)\n\n**4. Sulfonamides (Co-trimoxazole)**\n- Can cause **kernicterus** in infants\n- Especially dangerous in: Premature babies, G6PD deficiency\n- ‚ùå Avoid\n\n### ‚ö†Ô∏è USE WITH CAUTION (NOT FIRST CHOICE)\n\n**5. Metronidazole**\n- Enters breast milk\n- Short courses ‚Üí generally acceptable\n- High dose / prolonged use ‚Üí temporary breastfeeding interruption advised\n\n**6. Clindamycin**\n- May cause: Infant diarrhea, Pseudomembranous colitis\n- ‚ö†Ô∏è Use only if necessary\n\n### ‚úÖ SAFE ALTERNATIVES\n\n| Safe in Lactation | Examples |\n|-------------------|----------|\n| Penicillins | Amoxicillin |\n| Cephalosporins | Cephalexin |\n| Macrolides | Erythromycin, Azithromycin |\n\n---\n\n## üö® ECLAMPSIA ‚Äî DRUG OF CHOICE\n\nA woman with preeclampsia (hypertension after 20 weeks of pregnancy) is at risk of developing eclampsia.\n\nIn eclampsia, the management is different from routine epileptic seizures.\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">‚úÖ **Magnesium sulfate (MgSO‚ÇÑ) ‚Äî DRUG OF CHOICE**</span>\n\nFor seizures due to eclampsia, magnesium sulfate is the treatment of choice.\n\n| Condition | Drug of choice |\n|-----------|---------------|\n| Epileptic seizure | Midazolam (Adult dose ‚Üí 10 mg buccal/IN or 2.5‚Äì5 mg IV) |\n| Eclampsia | <span style="color: #ff0000">**Magnesium sulfate**</span> |\n\n### One more important fact\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">üîë **Exam one-liners:**</span>\n- Supine position in pregnancy causes ‚Üí **IVC compression**\n- Result ‚Üí supine hypotensive syndrome\n- Prevention ‚Üí **left lateral tilt**\n\n---\n\n## üîë HIGH-YIELD EXAM ONE-LINERS\n\n- Tetracyclines ‚Üí contraindicated in lactation\n- Chloramphenicol ‚Üí causes gray baby syndrome\n- Fluoroquinolones ‚Üí cartilage toxicity\n- Sulfonamides ‚Üí kernicterus\n- Opioids ‚Üí Respiratory depression\n\n### ü¶∑ Dental exam favorite\n\n- <span style="color: #ff0000">**Antibiotic contraindicated in lactating mother ‚Üí Tetracycline**</span>\n- Primary teeth affected if taken during pregnancy\n- Permanent teeth affected if taken in early childhood\n\n---\n\n## üç∫ Fetal Alcohol Syndrome (FAS) ‚Äî FEATURES\n\n### üë∂ Characteristic Facial Features\n\n- Short palpebral fissures\n- <span style="color: #ff0000">**Smooth / flat philtrum**</span>\n- <span style="color: #ff0000">**Thin upper lip**</span>\n- Flat midface\n- Low nasal bridge\n- Epicanthal folds (may be present)\n\n<span style="color: #ff0000">üìå **Smooth philtrum + thin upper lip = hallmark**</span>\n\n<div align="center">\n  <img src="/assets/embryology/image9.png" alt="Fetal Alcohol Syndrome" width="500" />\n</div>\n\n\n---\n\n## Key Developmental Periods\n\n- **Embryonic period:** 3‚Äì8 weeks ‚Üí Organogenesis (formation of organs)\n- **Fetal period:** 9 weeks ‚Üí birth ‚Üí Growth and maturation of organs\n',a=[{id:"emb-easy-1",question:"Which of the following structures is derived from neural crest cells?",options:["Enamel","Dentin","Oral epithelium","Myoblasts of tongue"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"Neural crest ectomesenchyme gives rise to dentin, pulp, and cementum. Enamel is from oral ectoderm."},{id:"emb-easy-2",question:"Ovulated cell in humans is arrested in:",options:["Prophase I","Metaphase I","Metaphase II","Anaphase II"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"The secondary oocyte is arrested in metaphase II until fertilization occurs."},{id:"emb-easy-3",question:"The hormone responsible for maintenance of corpus luteum in early pregnancy is:",options:["Estrogen","Progesterone","hCG","Prolactin"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"hCG (human chorionic gonadotropin) maintains the corpus luteum, which secretes progesterone and estrogen."},{id:"emb-easy-4",question:"Which germ layer gives rise to enamel?",options:["Mesoderm","Endoderm","Oral ectoderm","Neural crest"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Enamel is derived from oral ectoderm via ameloblasts."},{id:"emb-easy-5",question:"Site of fertilization in humans is:",options:["Infundibulum","Ampulla","Isthmus","Uterus"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"Fertilization occurs in the ampulla of the uterine tube."}],o=[{id:"emb-med-1",question:"Which of the following is NOT a derivative of neural crest cells?",options:["Odontoblasts","Schwann cells","Melanocytes","Skeletal muscle of tongue"],correctAnswerIndex:3,explanation:"Tongue muscles are derived from occipital somites, not neural crest cells."},{id:"emb-med-2",question:"Failure of posterior neuropore closure leads to:",options:["Anencephaly","Encephalocele","Spina bifida","Holoprosencephaly"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Posterior neuropore failure causes spina bifida. Anterior neuropore failure causes anencephaly."},{id:"emb-med-3",question:"Which structure initiates neurulation?",options:["Neural plate","Neural crest","Notochord","Epiblast"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"The notochord initiates neurulation by inducing formation of the neural plate."},{id:"emb-med-4",question:"Which placental component is fetal in origin?",options:["Decidua basalis","Decidua capsularis","Chorion frondosum","Syncytium alone"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Chorion frondosum is the fetal part of the placenta. Decidua basalis is maternal."},{id:"emb-med-5",question:"Primary villi are composed of:",options:["Trophoblast + mesoderm","Trophoblast + blood vessels","Trophoblast only","Mesoderm only"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Primary villi consist of trophoblast only. Secondary add mesoderm, tertiary add blood vessels."}],t=[{id:"emb-hard-1",question:"Completion of meiosis II in the oocyte occurs after:",options:["LH surge","Ovulation","Fertilization","Implantation"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Meiosis II is completed only after fertilization, not before."},{id:"emb-hard-2",question:"All are derivatives of neural crest cells EXCEPT:",options:["Cementoblasts","Pulp fibroblasts","Ameloblasts","Odontoblasts"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Ameloblasts are derived from oral ectoderm, not neural crest cells."},{id:"emb-hard-3",question:"Arrangement of microtubules in sperm tail is:",options:["9 √ó 3","9 + 0","8 + 2","9 + 2"],correctAnswerIndex:3,explanation:"The sperm flagellum has a 9+2 microtubule arrangement in its axoneme."},{id:"emb-hard-4",question:"Which of the following is derived from neural crest cells?",options:["Parotid gland","Submandibular gland","Adrenal medulla","Liver"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"The adrenal medulla (chromaffin cells) is derived from neural crest cells."},{id:"emb-hard-5",question:"Which neural crest derivative contributes to craniofacial skeleton?",options:["Paraxial mesoderm","Intermediate mesoderm","Ectomesenchyme","Endoderm"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Ectomesenchyme (neural crest origin) contributes to craniofacial bones and cartilage."},{id:"emb-hard-6",question:"IgM in fetal blood indicates:",options:["Passive immunity from mother","Active fetal infection","Normal development","Placental transfer"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"IgM does not cross the placenta, so its presence in fetal blood indicates intrauterine infection."},{id:"emb-hard-7",question:"Drug of choice for eclampsia is:",options:["Diazepam","Phenytoin","Magnesium sulfate","Midazolam"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Magnesium sulfate is the drug of choice for eclampsia, not regular anticonvulsants."},{id:"emb-hard-8",question:"Antibiotic contraindicated in lactation due to tooth discoloration:",options:["Amoxicillin","Tetracycline","Erythromycin","Cephalexin"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"Tetracyclines cause tooth discoloration and are contraindicated in lactation."}],i=[{id:"emb-ch-1",question:"Primary oocytes are formed before birth and remain arrested in which phase of meiosis I until puberty?",options:["Leptotene","Zygotene","Pachytene","Diplotene"],correctAnswerIndex:3,explanation:"Primary oocytes enter meiosis I before birth but are arrested in the diplotene stage of prophase I until puberty."},{id:"emb-ch-2",question:"The completion of the second meiotic division in a human female gamete is specifically triggered by:",options:["LH surge","Ovulation","Fertilization","Implantation"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Meiosis II is only completed after fertilization. If fertilization does not occur, the secondary oocyte degenerates while still in metaphase II."},{id:"emb-ch-3",question:"During the 3rd week of development (Gastrulation), the primitive streak is formed by the migration of cells from which layer?",options:["Hypoblast","Cytotrophoblast","Epiblast","Syncytiotrophoblast"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Gastrulation begins with the formation of the primitive streak on the surface of the epiblast."},{id:"emb-ch-4",question:"Which of the following muscles is uniquely derived from the 4th pharyngeal arch rather than occipital somites?",options:["Hyoglossus","Styloglossus","Genioglossus","Palatoglossus"],correctAnswerIndex:3,explanation:"All tongue muscles derive from occipital somites EXECPT the palatoglossus, which comes from the 4th pharyngeal arch (CN X)."},{id:"emb-ch-5",question:"Failure of the anterior neuropore to close results in which serious congenital defect, and when does it normally close?",options:["Anencephaly; Day 25","Spina Bifida; Day 27","Anencephaly; Day 27","Spina Bifida; Day 25"],correctAnswerIndex:0,explanation:"Anterior neuropore failure causes anencephaly (Day 25). Posterior failure causes spina bifida (Day 27)."},{id:"emb-ch-6",question:"Which specific immunoglobulin class is used to assess intrauterine fetal infection because it cannot cross the placental barrier?",options:["IgG","IgA","IgM","IgE"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"IgM does not cross the placenta. Its presence in fetal blood indicates the fetus has produced it in response to an infection."},{id:"emb-ch-7",question:'In a pregnant patient, the supine position can lead to "Supine Hypotensive Syndrome" primarily due to compression of:',options:["Abdominal Aorta","Inferior Vena Cava","Common Iliac Artery","Renal Vein"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"The heavy uterus compresses the IVC in the supine position, reducing venous return and causing hypotension."},{id:"emb-ch-8",question:"A neonate presents with Hutchinson incisors and mulberry molars. This is a classic sign of which congenital infection?",options:["Toxoplasmosis","Rubella","Cytomegalovirus","Syphilis"],correctAnswerIndex:3,explanation:"Hutchinson's triad (including dental anomalies) is characteristic of congenital syphilis."},{id:"emb-ch-9",question:"Which antibiotic is strictly contraindicated in lactating mothers because it can cause suppression of bone growth in the infant?",options:["Amoxicillin","Tetracycline","Clindamycin","Metronidazole"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"Tetracyclines cause tooth discoloration and inhibit bone growth by chelating calcium."},{id:"emb-ch-10",question:"For a patient experiencing a seizure due to Eclampsia, the pharmaceutical agent of choice for management is:",options:["Midazolam","Diazepam","Magnesium Sulfate","Phenobarbital"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"MgSO4 is the drug of choice for eclampsia-related seizures, whereas benzodiazepines are used for status epilepticus."},{id:"emb-ch-11",question:'The "notochord," which induces the formation of the neural plate, eventually degenerates and persists only as:',options:["Spinal Cord","Vertebral Body","Nucleus Pulposus","Annulus Fibrosus"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"The notochord induces neurulation and then disappears, leaving the nucleus pulposus in intervertebral discs as its remnant."},{id:"emb-ch-12",question:"During the maturation of chorionic villi, gas and nutrient exchange between maternal and fetal blood begins specifically at the:",options:["Primary villus stage","Secondary villus stage","Tertiary villus stage","Quaternary villus stage"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Tertiary villi contain fetal blood vessels, which are necessary for exchange."},{id:"emb-ch-13",question:'Fetal Alcohol Syndrome (FAS) is characterized by a "hallmark" facial appearance. Which feature is most representative?',options:["High nasal bridge","Prominent philtrum","Smooth philtrum and thin upper lip","Thick lower lip"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"A smooth/flat philtrum and very thin upper lip are diagnostic hallmarks of FAS."},{id:"emb-ch-14",question:"Which of the following glands is the only major salivary gland of ectodermal origin?",options:["Parotid gland","Submandibular gland","Sublingual gland","Minor salivary glands"],correctAnswerIndex:0,explanation:"The parotid is ectodermal, while the submandibular and sublingual are endodermal."},{id:"emb-ch-15",question:"Cleavage of the zygote results in the formation of a 16‚Äì32 cell solid ball known as the Morula. What is unique about this stage?",options:["It is larger than the zygote","It contains a fluid-filled cavity","There is no increase in overall size from the zygote","Cells have already differentiated into fetal organs"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Cleavage consists of rapid mitotic divisions without growth, so the morula is roughly the same size as the original zygote."},{id:"emb-ch-16",question:"The acrosome reaction, which allows the sperm to penetrate the egg, is primarily triggered by contact with which layer?",options:["Corona radiata","Zona pellucida","Vitelline membrane","Plasma membrane of oocyte"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"Binding of sperm to the ZP3 receptor on the zona pellucida triggers the acrosome reaction."},{id:"emb-ch-17",question:"Which specific layer of the trophoblast is multinucleated, lacks cell boundaries, and is responsible for the secretion of hCG?",options:["Cytotrophoblast","Syncytiotrophoblast","Hypoblast","Extraembryonic mesoderm"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"The syncytiotrophoblast is the outer invading layer that lacks distinct cell boundaries and produces human chorionic gonadotropin."},{id:"emb-ch-18",question:'Failure of fusion between which two processes results in the formation of a "Cleft Lip"?',options:["Maxillary prominence and Lateral nasal prominence","Maxillary prominence and Medial nasal prominence","Medial nasal prominence and Lateral nasal prominence","Palatal shelves and Primary palate"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"Cleft lip results from the failure of fusion between the maxillary prominence and the medial nasal prominence."},{id:"emb-ch-19",question:"The first pharyngeal arch (Mandibular arch) is associated with which cranial nerve?",options:["CN V (Trigeminal)","CN VII (Facial)","CN IX (Glossopharyngeal)","CN X (Vagus)"],correctAnswerIndex:0,explanation:"The first arch is supplied by the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve (CN V)."},{id:"emb-ch-20",question:"The taste buds of the anterior two-thirds of the tongue are innervated by which nerve?",options:["Lingual nerve (CN V3)","Chorda tympani (CN VII)","Glossopharyngeal (CN IX)","Hypoglossal (CN XII)"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"General sensation is via the lingual nerve (CN V3), but special sensation (taste) for the anterior 2/3 is via the chorda tympani (CN VII)."},{id:"emb-ch-21",question:"Which placental layer significantly thins or disappears after the 4th month to facilitate more efficient exchange between mother and fetus?",options:["Syncytiotrophoblast","Cytotrophoblast","Basement membrane","Endothelium of fetal capillaries"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"The cytotrophoblast layer disappears in the latter half of pregnancy, leaving a thinner barrier for exchange."},{id:"emb-ch-22",question:"The Umbilical Vein is structurally unique compared to typical veins because it carries:",options:["Deoxygenated blood toward the placenta","Oxygenated blood toward the placenta","Deoxygenated blood toward the fetal heart","Oxygenated blood toward the fetal heart"],correctAnswerIndex:3,explanation:"The umbilical vein carries nutrient-rich, oxygenated blood from the placenta to the fetus."},{id:"emb-ch-23",question:"When does the concentration of human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) typically reach its peak during pregnancy?",options:["4th week","10th week","20th week","38th week"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"hCG production peaks at approximately 8‚Äì10 weeks of gestation before declining."},{id:"emb-ch-24",question:"What is the most common congenital viral infection worldwide, often presenting with microcephaly and sensorineural hearing loss?",options:["Rubella","Cytomegalovirus (CMV)","Herpes Simplex Virus","Toxoplasmosis"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"CMV is the most frequent congenital viral infection and a leading cause of non-hereditary hearing loss."},{id:"emb-ch-25",question:'The "Gray Baby Syndrome" is a life-threatening toxicity associated with the use of which antibiotic in neonates?',options:["Tetracycline","Chloramphenicol","Metronidazole","Clindamycin"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"Neonates cannot adequately metabolize chloramphenicol, leading to toxic accumulation and the characteristic gray appearance."},{id:"emb-ch-26",question:"Use of NSAIDs like Ibuprofen is strictly contraindicated in the 3rd trimester because it may cause:",options:["Gray baby syndrome","Kernicterus","Premature closure of the ductus arteriosus","Absence of digit formation"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Prostaglandins keep the ductus arteriosus open; inhibiting them with NSAIDs can cause its premature closure in utero."},{id:"emb-ch-27",question:"Rathke's pouch, an outpocketing of the oral ectoderm, gives rise to which endocrine structure?",options:["Adrenal medulla","Neurohypophysis (Posterior pituitary)","Adenohypophysis (Anterior pituitary)","Thyroid gland"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"The anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis) is derived from Rathke's pouch (oral ectoderm)."},{id:"emb-ch-28",question:"The stomodeum (primitive mouth) is initially separated from the foregut by which structure?",options:["Cloacal membrane","Buccopharyngeal membrane","Neural plate","Neural crest"],correctAnswerIndex:1,explanation:"The buccopharyngeal (oropharyngeal) membrane separates the ectodermal stomodeum from the endodermal foregut."},{id:"emb-ch-29",question:"All muscles of the tongue are derived from occipital somites, EXCEPT for one muscle. Which one is the exception?",options:["Genioglossus","Hyoglossus","Palatoglossus","Styloglossus"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Palatoglossus is the only tongue muscle NOT derived from somites; it comes from the 4th pharyngeal arch."},{id:"emb-ch-30",question:"Which of the following is the specific site where sperm capacitation normally occurs?",options:["Seminiferous tubules","Epididymis","Uterus and Uterine tubes","Vaginal canal"],correctAnswerIndex:2,explanation:"Capacitation is a 7-hour maturation process that occurs entirely within the female reproductive tract."}];export{e as G,n as a,o as b,i as c,t as d,a as e};
